Bank Churn Prediction

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses, such as banks that offer services, must address the issue of 'Customer Churn,' which refers to customers leaving to join another service provider. Understanding the factors that influence a customer's decision to stay or leave is crucial. By identifying these key aspects of their service, management can focus on targeted improvements, ensuring efforts are directed towards enhancing the most critical areas to retain customers.

Objective¶

As a Data Scientist, the task is to develop a neural network-based classifier capable of predicting whether a customer will leave the bank within the next six months.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts, plot a stacked bar chart, and perform a chi-square test.

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 50)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))

    # Perform chi-square test of independence
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target])
    chi2, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

    # Define significance level
    alpha = 0.05

    # Determine the hypothesis based on p-value
    if p_value < alpha:
        significance = "reject"
        statement = f"There is a significant association between {predictor} and {target} with p-value {p_value:.3f} < 0.05. \n We reject the null hypothesis."
    else:
        significance = "accept"
        statement = f"There is no significant association between {predictor} and {target} with p-value {p_value:.3f} > 0.05. \n We fail to reject the null hypothesis."

    # Add the statement at the bottom of the plot
    plt.figtext(0.5, -0.1, statement, ha='center', fontsize=10, bbox={"facecolor":"none", "alpha":0.5, "pad":5, "edgecolor": "none"})
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    print("-" * 50)

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    """
    Plots the distribution and relationship between a predictor and target variable.

    Parameters:
    - data: Dataset containing the predictor and target
    - predictor: Independent variable
    - target: target variable

    Calculates and displays the Pearson correlation coefficient and significance.
    """

    # Create a 2x2 grid of subplots
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )
    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))

    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )
    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))

    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")
    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")

    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )
    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")

    # Calculate Pearson correlation coefficient and p-value
    corr, p_value = stats.pearsonr(data[predictor], data[target])

    # Define significance level
    alpha = 0.05

    # Determine the hypothesis based on p-value
    if p_value < alpha:
        significance = "reject"
        statement = f"There is a significant difference between {predictor} and {target} with a correlation coefficient of {corr:.2f}, and p-value < 0.05. \n We reject the null hypothesis."
    else:
        significance = "accept"
        statement = f"There is no significant difference between {predictor} and {target} with a correlation coefficient of {corr:.2f}, and p-value > 0.05. \n We fail to reject the null hypothesis."

    # Print the statement at the bottom of the plot
    fig.text(0.1, -0.1, statement, ha='left')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    print("-" * 150)

  • It appears to be no significant difference in the distribution of Estimated Salary between customers who churned and those who did not. This is further supported by the correlation coefficient of 0.01 and p-value > 0.05, indicating a weak correlation and lack of statistical significance.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import pandas as pd

# Function to standardize data
def standardize_data(scaler, df, num_cols, cat_cols):
    num_subset = scaler.transform(df[num_cols])
    num_df = pd.DataFrame(num_subset, columns=num_cols)
    for col in cat_cols:
        num_df[col] = df[col].values
    return num_df

# Columns to be standardized and kept as is

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

For the task of customer churn prediction, we are choosing Recall as the primary metric because the cost of missing a churn prediction (false negative) is more significant than falsely predicting churn (false positive). Therefore, we will be selecting a model with high recall to ensure that most of the actual churned customers are identified.

Let's create a function for plotting the confusion matrix

In [36]:
def make_confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    actual_targets: actual target (dependent) variable values
    predicted_targets: predicted target (dependent) variable values
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(cm.shape[0], cm.shape[1])

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

For this analysis, we are going to train various Neural Network models and keep tracking of the recall values. In order to store the recall values from various models we are creating two dataframe that will store the recall values for all the models we build.

  • Recall improves for both training and validation sets over the epochs, but the widening gap between them suggests that the model is overfitting.

# Create a figure with two subplots side by side
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))  # 1 row, 2 columns

# Plot Train Loss vs Validation Loss
axs[0].plot(history_3.history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
axs[0].plot(history_3.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
axs[0].set_title('Model Loss')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Loss')
axs[0].set_xlabel('Epoch')
axs[0].legend(loc='upper left')

# Plot Train Recall vs Validation Recall
axs[1].plot(history_3.history['Recall'], label='Train Recall')
axs[1].plot(history_3.history['val_Recall'], label='Validation Recall')
axs[1].set_title('Model Recall')
axs[1].set_ylabel('Recall')
axs[1].set_xlabel('Epoch')
axs[1].legend(loc='upper left')

# Adjust layout to avoid overlap
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plots
plt.show()

  • After applying SMOTE the model performence is significantly improved.

  • Both training and validation loss curves have significantly decreased compared to the previous models. The narrow gap between the training and validation loss curves shows that the issue of overfitting is reduced but still exists.

  • The recall for both training and validation sets has increased substantially, indicating better performance in identifying positive cases. While there's still a gap between training and validation recall, it's notably smaller than in the previous models, suggesting improved generalization.

model_4 = Sequential()

model_4.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))

In [121]:

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights:¶

The followings are major insights drawn from the analysis of the given data.

Customer Segmentation by Age:¶

The dataset reveals two prominent age groups: younger adults (late 20s to early 30s) and middle-aged individuals (around 40 years old). This segmentation suggests the need for tailored marketing strategies targeting each group’s specific needs and preferences.

High Churn in Older Customers:¶

There is a statistically significant positive correlation between age and churn, with older customers more likely to leave. This indicates a need to create retention strategies specifically aimed at older customers, possibly through loyalty programs or age-appropriate products/services.

Account Balance as a Churn Indicator:¶

Customers with higher account balances are more likely to churn. These customers might require more personalized engagement or value-added services to prevent churn.

Product Ownership and Churn Risk:¶

Customers with more products (2) show a significantly lower churn rate, cross-selling additional products can be an effective retention strategy. However, there is an anomaly where customers with 3 or 4 products have extremely high churn rates. This suggests the need to investigate further, potentially revisiting the value proposition of these products or understanding the specific needs of these customers.

Geographic Insights:¶

Germany has the highest rate of customer churn among the three countries (France, Germany, Spain). This indicates the need for a targeted retention strategy in Germany, potentially exploring local market conditions.

Active Membership as a Key Retention Factor:¶

Active members are significantly less likely to churn compared to inactive members. This highlights the importance of encouraging active engagement with the company's services such as regular check-ins, loyalty rewards, or personalized offers to inactive members.

Credit Card Ownership Not a Churn Predictor:¶

There is no significant difference in churn rates between customers with or without credit cards. This indicates that ownership of credit card should not be a focus for churn prediction or prevention.

Gender-Based Churn Patterns:¶

Females are more likely to churn compared to males. This suggests a potential need for gender-specific retention strategies.

Business Recommendations:¶

Develop Age-Specific Engagement Programs:¶

Create targeted marketing campaigns and product offerings that cater to the two identified age groups.

Retention Strategies for High-Balance Customers:¶

Implement personalized financial planning services, loyalty rewards, or exclusive offers for customers with higher account balances to reduce their likelihood of churn.

Enhance Cross-Selling Efforts:¶

Actively promote the benefits of holding multiple products, particularly focusing on customers who currently own only one product.

Focus on Germany for Retention:¶

Investigate the specific reasons behind the high churn rate in Germany and tailor retention strategies to address these issues. Consider localizing offers, improving customer support, or enhancing the user experience in this region.

Increase Customer Engagement:¶

Develop initiatives to boost active membership.

Address Gender-Based Churn:¶

Conduct further analysis to understand why female customers are more likely to churn and develop targeted retention strategies that address their specific concerns.

Monitor Tenure Milestones:¶

Implement a proactive customer engagement program that targets customers approaching the 10-year tenure mark.

Focus on Recall in Churn Prediction Models:¶

Prioritize models with high recall in churn prediction to ensure that the majority of potential churners are identified, thereby allowing for timely intervention and retention efforts.
